# College of Southern Nevada

The **College of Southern Nevada (CSN)** is a [public](/Public_college) [community college](/Community_college) located in [Clark County, Nevada](/Clark_County,_Nevada), United States. It is the largest public institution of higher education in Nevada, serving over 30,000 students annually. CSN is part of the [Nevada System of Higher Education](/Nevada_System_of_Higher_Education) and offers a wide range of academic programs, including associate degrees, certificates, and bachelor's degrees.

## History

CSN was founded in 1971 as **Clark County Community College**. In 1991, it was renamed the **Community College of Southern Nevada** to reflect its expanding role in the region. On March 16, 2007, the [Board of Regents](/Board_of_Regents) of the Nevada System of Higher Education voted to change the institution's name to the **College of Southern Nevada**, effective July 1, 2007. This change was made to better represent the college's comprehensive academic offerings and its status as a major educational institution in the state.

## Campuses

CSN operates three main campuses in the [Las Vegas Valley](/Las_Vegas_Valley):

- **West Charleston Campus**: Located in Las Vegas, this campus is the largest and serves as the administrative hub of the college.
- **North Las Vegas Campus**: Situated in North Las Vegas, this campus offers a variety of academic and technical programs.
- **Henderson Campus**: Located in Henderson, this campus is home to the college's athletic facilities and several specialized programs.

In addition to its main campuses, CSN operates seven learning centers throughout the region:

- Moapa Valley
- Summerlin
- Mesquite
- Green Valley
- Western
- Sahara West
- [Nellis Air Force Base](/Nellis_Air_Force_Base)

These centers provide educational opportunities to students in more remote areas of Clark County.

## Academics

CSN offers job training in more than 70 academic programs, with over 180 degree and certificate options available. The college also offers fifteen bachelor's degrees, making it a comprehensive institution for students seeking both two-year and four-year degrees. As of the most recent data, 73.5% of students attend part-time, while 26.5% attend full-time.

The college is organized into several schools and departments:

- **School of Advanced and Applied Technologies**
- **School of Arts and Letters**
- **School of Business, Hospitality and Public Services**
- **School of Education, Behavioral and Social Sciences**
- **Ralph & Betty Engelstad School of Health Sciences**
- **School of Science, Engineering and Mathematics**
- **Division of Workforce and Economic Development**

CSN has been accredited by the [Northwest Commission on Colleges and Universities](/Northwest_Commission_on_Colleges_and_Universities) since 1975, ensuring that its academic programs meet high standards of quality and rigor.

## Student Life

CSN has a diverse student body, with a significant portion of students identifying as Hispanic, making it a [Hispanic Serving Institution](/Hispanic-serving_institution). As of Fall 2024, the undergraduate demographics are as follows:

- **Hispanic**: 41%
- **White**: 25%
- **Black**: 11%
- **Asian**: 9%
- **Two or more races**: 8%
- **Unknown**: 5%
- **Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander**: 1%
- **International student**: 1%

In terms of economic diversity, 31% of students are considered low-income, while 69% are affluent.

## Athletics

The College of Southern Nevada Coyotes compete in the [Arizona Community College Athletic Conference](/Arizona_Community_College_Athletic_Conference) of the [NJCAA's Division I](/National_Junior_College_Athletic_Association). The college currently has five athletic programs:

- **Men's baseball**
- **Men's soccer**
- **Women's softball**
- **Women's volleyball**
- **Women's soccer**

### Baseball

The Coyotes baseball team was the first intercollegiate athletics program at CSN. The team's home field, William R. Morse Stadium, is located at the Henderson campus. The program has a rich history, including a national championship in 2003. Notable alumni include [Bryce Harper](/Bryce_Harper), who was selected first overall by the [Washington Nationals](/Washington_Nationals) in the 2010 Major League Baseball Draft.

### Softball

The Coyotes softball team debuted in the spring of 2004. The team's home field is located at the Russell Road Recreation Complex in Henderson. The program has enjoyed several winning seasons and continues to grow in popularity.

### Soccer

CSN added men's and women's soccer programs in the fall of 2016. Both teams have quickly become competitive, with the men's team making it to the NJCAA Division I Men's Soccer Championship in their inaugural season.

